<div type="description" n="monument">
<head>Description of Monument</head>
<p>White marble <rs type="objectType">sarcophagus</rs>, decorated with <rs type="decoration">columns</rs> and <rs type="decoration">garland</rs>s, and with a <rs type="decoration">recumbent figure</rs> on the lid, which is broken to right (<measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="width">2.25</measure>   × <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height">1.35</measure>   × <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="depth">0.93</measure>). See now Isik 157
</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="text">
<head>Description of Text</head>
<p><rs type="execution" key="scalpro">Inscribed</rs> (l.1) along front of lid (<measure dim="width" type="length" unit="metre">1.50</measure>   × <measure dim="height" type="length" unit="metre">0.07</measure>) and in <rs type="decoration">tabella ansata</rs> (<measure dim="width" type="length" unit="metre">0.29</measure>   × <measure dim="height" type="length" unit="metre">0.45</measure>); apparently reused.</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="letters" sample="complete" org="uniform">
<head>Letters</head>
<p> Individually quite well designed, but less well cut and, in the tabella, poorly aligned with very uneven heights, <measure dim="height" type="length" unit="metre">0.045-0.065</measure>; probably second to third centuries; Ϲ and for sigma, often oval omicron, v for hypsilon. Unconventional spelling in l.1.</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="date" sample="complete" org="uniform">
<head>Date</head>
<p>
Perhaps <date notBefore="0168" notAfter="0233" exact="none" cert="low"> late second to early  third centuries</date>
 (<rs type="criteria">lettering</rs>, <rs type="criteria">nomenclature</rs>).</p>
</div>
<div type="edition" lang="grc">
<head lang="en">Edition</head>
<ab><lb n="1"/> <w lemma="ὁ">ἡ</w> <w lemma="σορός">σορός</w> <w lemma="εἰμί">ἐστιν</w> <w lemma="καί">κὲ</w> <w lemma="ὁ">ὁ</w> <w lemma="τόπος">τό<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">πος</supplied></w>    <gap reason="lost" extent="6" unit="character" extentmax="7"/>  <lb n="2"/><persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Διονύσιος">Διονυ<lb n="3" type="worddiv"/>σίου</name>  <lb n="4"/><g type="leaf"/>  <num value="4">δ</num>  <g type="leaf"/>  <lb n="5"/><persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Διογενιανός">Διογε<lb n="6" type="worddiv"/>νια<lb n="7" type="worddiv"/>νοῦ</name></persName></persName>  </ab>
</div>

<div type="translation" sample="complete" org="uniform">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>The sarcophagus and the plot <gap reason="lost" extent="6" unit="character" extentmax="7"/> belong to Dionysios, fourth of the name from Diogenianos.</p>
</div>
<div type="commentary" sample="complete" org="uniform">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>It is not certain that we have the owner's full name, since either a short Greek name or an abbreviated Roman praenomen and nomen, e.g. <foreign lang="grc">Μ(άρκου) Αὐρηλ(ίου)</foreign>, could have stood at the end of l.1. If the name was wholly Greek he presumably died before the Edict of Caracalla in A.D. 212; if he had Roman citizenship it may well have been after that, but his genealogy suggests (although it does not prove) that he was the first Roman citizen in the family.</p>
</div>
